AB  - In directing climate action, states are faced with three core governance challenges coordination, consensus building, and strategy setting. Successful implementation of ambitious near and long-term mitigation and adaptation targets under the Paris Agreement will therefore require robust institutional frameworks. Assessing national progress on institutional development could be advanced by the global stocktake, and is as crucial to the success of mitigation and adaptation goals as the assessment of policies and targets. Tracking institutional development is, however, complex because countries generally follow path-dependent institutional trajectories contingent on national context. With this important caveat, we present information to show that countries currently differ in their levels of climate institutional development along these three parameters. Key Messages - State capacity in the form of climate institutions capable of informing target-setting, converting targets to policies, a
