AB  - • The lack of observational climate data in Africa is recognized as a constraint to understanding current and future climate variability. Significant gaps are apparent in the surface network, including in Angola, the Congo basin, and Sudan, and parts of the Sahel. • Regional requirements for increasing Africa’s contribution to the global climate observing system have been identified by regional workshops and the regional action plans that followed. Requirements include improving and sustaining operational observing networks, such as the GCOS Surface and Upper Air Networks (GSN and GUAN); recovering historical data; improving national and regional coordination; education, training and capacity building; and improved national planning and reporting. More stations are needed and of those that are in place many are not reporting or are reporting at a substandard level. Africa also has a low density of WMO World Weather Watch real time weather stations, in fact, the lowest of any region in
